1
00:00:00,620 --> 00:00:02,060
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,140 --> 00:00:11,240
Today I'll walk through the method for finding the push-pull operating frequency for this coil.

3
00:00:11,400 --> 00:00:19,360
So that wave processes happen inside it, and the coil heats up without a load.

4
00:00:20,580 --> 00:00:23,240
That is, so the current really ramps up in the system.

5
00:00:23,620 --> 00:00:32,600
Now we'll test it and see which frequencies people always end up using versus which ones are actually needed.

6
00:00:33,380 --> 00:00:45,020
For this we need this helper tool — a ferrite ring, mark 1500–2000, can be higher, doesn't matter.

7
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:50,700
Wind 8–10 turns; no resistor needed, we're not tracking exact phasing.

8
00:00:51,460 --> 00:00:59,460
We just need to know the current amplitude in the system.

9
00:01:00,160 --> 00:01:01,800
Here's how it works.

10
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:17,360
When electric current moves through a conductor, or charges are stationary but spin rotation is happening, a magnetic field forms around the conductor.

11
00:01:17,360 --> 00:01:30,300
When you put this ring over the conductor, it captures the magnetic field and the turns convert it into a voltage we can read on the oscilloscope.

12
00:01:31,260 --> 00:01:48,660
To track current movement in this coil, we need to short the coil leads to each other physically — galvanically — and that lets us see when the coil is working in half-wave mode.

13
00:01:50,620 --> 00:01:51,880
Where do we start?

14
00:01:52,940 --> 00:01:56,780
Put the ring over one of the leads, with the leads shorted,

15
00:01:59,870 --> 00:02:05,110
make good contact and hook up the oscilloscope.

16
00:02:07,370 --> 00:02:08,870
Phasing doesn't matter.

17
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:14,620
Common and the probe itself.

18
00:02:16,220 --> 00:02:22,880
For instruments we'll also need a signal generator and an oscilloscope.

19
00:02:23,820 --> 00:02:30,820
The signal generator output hooks directly to the coil's inductor.

20
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:35,760
And then we'll see what shows up on the instruments.

21
00:02:37,220 --> 00:02:39,260
Now we see —

22
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:47,540
let's feed in 5 kHz to start.

23
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:50,640
Feed a sine wave,

24
00:02:53,900 --> 00:02:55,780
amplitude on.

25
00:02:56,260 --> 00:03:00,340
Our peak-to-peak amplitude is 10 volts.

26
00:03:02,640 --> 00:03:09,060
And now we'll sweep the frequency and watch what happens on the oscillogram.

27
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:26,940
Passing through the usual operating range — somewhere between 10 and 45–50 kHz.

28
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:32,320
Where practically everyone works.

29
00:03:32,420 --> 00:03:44,380
And we see that staying around 25 kHz makes no sense, because the current amplitude is at its minimum at that frequency.

30
00:03:45,540 --> 00:03:46,300
Moving on.

31
00:03:49,400 --> 00:03:54,740
Past 60 kHz, and the amplitude is starting to grow.

32
00:03:57,220 --> 00:03:58,120
Looking further.

33
00:04:00,500 --> 00:04:06,260
Look at the range we've passed through.

34
00:04:06,600 --> 00:04:17,860
Amplitude is now at 0.2 V per division.

35
00:04:20,500 --> 00:04:23,320
Nothing remarkable yet.

36
00:04:24,340 --> 00:04:25,420
Moving on.

37
00:04:34,060 --> 00:04:36,740
Amplitude isn't changing much.

38
00:04:37,720 --> 00:04:43,040
We can speed things up — not 1 kHz at a time, 10 kHz.

39
00:04:43,380 --> 00:04:51,520
Look — already at 500 kHz and the amplitude hasn't shifted significantly.

40
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:08,340
And only starting from 800 kHz do we see a jump in amplitude.

41
00:05:10,700 --> 00:05:13,720
Amplitude keeps climbing.

42
00:05:15,260 --> 00:05:20,020
Reached maximum around 910 kHz.

43
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:25,480
A push-pull obviously can't work at that frequency.

44
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:31,980
We have one option — work at a sub-multiple of this frequency.

45
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:37,560
If it's 910 kHz here, we can work at 91 kHz.

46
00:05:38,420 --> 00:05:43,500
Now we'll check what else might be interesting at this frequency.

47
00:05:49,750 --> 00:06:04,610
If we put a hand on the coil at this frequency, we can check how surrounding objects affect it.

48
00:06:05,670 --> 00:06:09,330
We want frequencies that are stable.

49
00:06:10,590 --> 00:06:11,570
Watching.

50
00:06:16,340 --> 00:06:21,040
Now I'll put my hand on the coil and we'll see the amplitude.

51
00:06:23,740 --> 00:06:27,520
Put my hand on — you can see the amplitude grows.

52
00:06:27,720 --> 00:06:31,460
Put it here in the reverse-turn zone.

53
00:06:32,820 --> 00:06:34,480
Amplitude grows.

54
00:06:36,400 --> 00:06:38,900
Now let's keep sweeping the frequency.

55
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:42,000
980 kHz.

56
00:06:42,080 --> 00:06:43,420
Amplitude grows here too.

57
00:06:44,660 --> 00:06:46,600
1000 kHz.

58
00:06:46,820 --> 00:06:48,500
Small growth too.

59
00:06:50,140 --> 00:06:52,940
1100 kHz.

60
00:06:52,940 --> 00:06:54,700
Growth is minimal.

61
00:06:55,620 --> 00:07:07,500
Our window of opportunity comes out somewhere from 850 to 1100 kHz.

62
00:07:07,500 --> 00:07:12,480
We've found our first range, and now we can write it down.

63
00:07:14,520 --> 00:07:15,480
Writing it down.

64
00:07:23,820 --> 00:07:28,740
830–1100 kHz.

65
00:07:29,300 --> 00:07:35,360
That's our window for the sub-multiple that we'll try to run the push-pull at.

66
00:07:36,360 --> 00:07:51,620
Next we'll see whether there's some higher-frequency current component in the system where current growth will be even greater.

67
00:07:52,260 --> 00:07:53,380
Sweeping by frequency.

68
00:08:01,340 --> 00:08:07,080
Sweeping through the range and no significant amplitude growth showing up.

69
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,260
Looking for the next clear jump.

70
00:08:17,820 --> 00:08:21,360
10 kHz step — that's acceptable.

71
00:08:22,620 --> 00:08:26,700
At 3800 the amplitude actually drops.

72
00:08:29,060 --> 00:08:33,060
Here — we caught it.

73
00:08:34,060 --> 00:08:44,160
Starting at 3910 kHz we have a sharp amplitude rise.

74
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:47,500
Now we sweep more carefully.

75
00:08:50,280 --> 00:08:52,060
Climbing, climbing.

76
00:08:53,620 --> 00:08:59,080
Good growth — can even switch the sweep to half a volt per division.

77
00:09:00,980 --> 00:09:03,720
Still seeing growth.

78
00:09:05,940 --> 00:09:08,320
1 volt per division.

79
00:09:13,850 --> 00:09:23,590
And here the drop starts at about 4650 kHz.

80
00:09:25,170 --> 00:09:31,570
Maximum amplitude at 4620–630.

81
00:09:32,570 --> 00:09:36,910
That's our second maximum.

82
00:09:37,250 --> 00:09:38,550
Writing it down.

83
00:09:47,890 --> 00:09:52,770
4620–4630 kHz.

84
00:09:54,530 --> 00:09:58,050
Let's see the effect of putting a hand near the coil at this frequency.

85
00:09:58,050 --> 00:10:03,330
At such high frequencies, losses usually show up.

86
00:10:06,170 --> 00:10:11,870
These frequencies aren't as stable, but the amplitude is at its peak.

87
00:10:12,390 --> 00:10:13,730
That's a normal process.

88
00:10:15,610 --> 00:10:18,890
Let's see — maybe we can find something else.

89
00:10:23,180 --> 00:10:25,380
Next, amplitude decrease.

90
00:10:32,830 --> 00:10:36,590
Going faster — 100 kHz steps.

91
00:10:37,290 --> 00:10:39,510
There's another small peak here.

92
00:10:40,430 --> 00:10:42,690
Found one at 7600.

93
00:10:43,930 --> 00:10:47,790
These frequencies are too high to be useful to us anymore.

94
00:10:47,950 --> 00:10:52,970
And further out at 11 MHz.

95
00:10:54,130 --> 00:10:58,770
That high a frequency is out of reach for our systems, not needed.

96
00:10:58,770 --> 00:11:01,950
And at that frequency, results are very unstable.

97
00:11:02,350 --> 00:11:05,610
At 8800, the amplitude isn't that big.

98
00:11:05,710 --> 00:11:09,790
And the effect of touching the coil is huge.

99
00:11:11,690 --> 00:11:19,790
In practice we've identified two operating frequencies where current is at its maximum.

100
00:11:19,850 --> 00:11:21,150
One of them is stable.

101
00:11:26,310 --> 00:11:28,290
Our next steps.

102
00:11:28,290 --> 00:11:33,290
Now we need to find a sub-multiple within this range.

103
00:11:34,310 --> 00:11:40,970
That, by spectrum analysis, hits this strong frequency.

104
00:11:42,250 --> 00:11:51,330
And whose, say, tenth harmonic would excite one of the frequencies in this range.

105
00:11:53,290 --> 00:12:00,750
Next we'll need to switch the oscilloscope to spectrum analyzer mode.

106
00:12:01,250 --> 00:12:05,010
The so-called FFT mode — fast Fourier transform.

107
00:12:05,790 --> 00:12:10,150
And check the spectrogram of this signal.

108
00:12:10,150 --> 00:12:21,790
So, our window of opportunity is from 83 to 110 kHz, as a sub-multiple.

109
00:12:23,390 --> 00:12:30,310
Switching the oscilloscope to spectrum analyzer mode.

110
00:12:32,930 --> 00:12:35,210
Here it is — FFT mode.

111
00:12:39,220 --> 00:12:45,340
And what to know about taking measurements this way.

112
00:12:46,360 --> 00:12:59,240
You can't actually measure signal harmonics with a sine wave — they'd show up in the spectrum as graphs in decibels.

113
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:02,580
With a sine wave signal.

114
00:13:03,580 --> 00:13:07,580
Let me show you.

115
00:13:10,080 --> 00:13:13,100
Right now 83 kHz is being fed to the input.

116
00:13:15,820 --> 00:13:17,160
And if we look,

117
00:13:20,790 --> 00:13:33,410
in this mode the device only shows the central frequency being fed in on the sine.

118
00:13:33,410 --> 00:13:42,670
In this case, that's 83 kHz.

119
00:13:44,470 --> 00:13:48,610
Now we'll set the sweep per division.

120
00:13:49,390 --> 00:13:58,630
We're interested in a sweep of around 50 kHz per division for the spectrum analyzer.

121
00:14:00,390 --> 00:14:03,610
Can now disable the first output,

122
00:14:07,270 --> 00:14:08,710
so it doesn't get in the way.

123
00:14:08,830 --> 00:14:12,870
And now we can observe the spectral picture.

124
00:14:14,650 --> 00:14:21,390
Remember, the signal generator is in sine mode.

125
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:26,670
What do we see here?

126
00:14:31,060 --> 00:14:38,540
At the center crosshair is the frequency.

127
00:14:42,280 --> 00:14:52,400
And if we line up the central peak in decibels at the center, we'll know its frequency.

128
00:14:52,400 --> 00:14:59,980
For example, place the center here and we see our 83 kHz.

129
00:15:00,160 --> 00:15:02,180
Let me show where it's displayed.

130
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:07,220
On my device, it's shown in the lower-left corner.

131
00:15:07,700 --> 00:15:12,420
There it is — 83 kHz, right in the center.

132
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:21,540
So we see that what we feed in as a sine, the device detects.

133
00:15:21,540 --> 00:15:30,160
To excite harmonics, we need to feed in a signal with steep edges.

134
00:15:30,400 --> 00:15:36,360
Which means switching the signal generator to square wave.

135
00:15:37,280 --> 00:15:38,080
Switching.

136
00:15:39,500 --> 00:15:43,740
Now you can see our picture has changed.

137
00:15:44,280 --> 00:15:58,300
We can see a series of frequencies stepped at multiples, spread over a spectrum range.

138
00:15:58,440 --> 00:16:01,200
And now the next part of the search method.

139
00:16:02,200 --> 00:16:16,200
We've determined that our highest current amplitude is in the 4620–4630 kHz range.

140
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:32,620
Now, within our 83–110 kHz range, we want to find the frequency that gives the highest dB signal at those high frequencies.

141
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:36,980
Looking for our frequency.

142
00:16:41,520 --> 00:16:42,220
4000...

143
00:16:44,860 --> 00:16:45,560
600...

144
00:16:49,940 --> 00:16:52,260
Here we have 630.

145
00:16:57,330 --> 00:16:59,370
Fine-tuning.

146
00:17:12,800 --> 00:17:17,160
There they are — our 4630 MHz.

147
00:17:17,220 --> 00:17:20,140
We see it's right in the center.

148
00:17:20,620 --> 00:17:37,800
Now, by picking frequencies in our window of opportunity, we need to place the spectrogram peak at the center of the scale.

149
00:17:42,070 --> 00:17:45,850
And start searching by frequency.

150
00:17:45,870 --> 00:17:47,070
Very smoothly.

151
00:17:53,230 --> 00:17:56,290
Moving in tenths of a Hz.

152
00:18:00,090 --> 00:18:05,490
And here we see — first hit.

153
00:18:05,490 --> 00:18:06,530
Watching.

154
00:18:15,210 --> 00:18:24,490
4630 at 84.2 kHz.

155
00:18:24,590 --> 00:18:25,330
Writing it down.

156
00:18:28,150 --> 00:18:30,950
84.2.

157
00:18:31,630 --> 00:18:32,750
Moving on.

158
00:18:34,970 --> 00:18:36,030
There.

159
00:18:36,170 --> 00:18:38,190
Worth pointing out —

160
00:18:38,490 --> 00:18:39,770
84.2.

161
00:18:40,290 --> 00:18:45,210
There are side harmonics showing up here too.

162
00:18:45,370 --> 00:18:50,330
We want a cleaner spectrum, without side harmonics.

163
00:18:57,340 --> 00:18:57,680
There.

164
00:18:58,400 --> 00:19:00,800
That's roughly what the picture should look like.

165
00:19:04,630 --> 00:19:06,890
Here's another hit.

166
00:19:07,890 --> 00:19:14,630
At 87.4 kHz.

167
00:19:14,710 --> 00:19:17,890
But we also see side peaks.

168
00:19:20,650 --> 00:19:21,290
Writing it down.

169
00:19:22,050 --> 00:19:26,270
87.4 kHz.

170
00:19:27,850 --> 00:19:28,810
Moving on.

171
00:19:39,400 --> 00:19:43,260
And here we found a really good frequency.

172
00:19:43,260 --> 00:19:57,980
A clean hit, no strong side harmonics — 90.8 kHz.

173
00:19:59,440 --> 00:20:00,980
We can keep going.

174
00:20:07,620 --> 00:20:09,160
Another hit.

175
00:20:09,160 --> 00:20:18,520
94.5 kHz.

176
00:20:18,860 --> 00:20:21,600
Also a good frequency.

177
00:20:24,060 --> 00:20:25,220
Marking them.

178
00:20:26,560 --> 00:20:27,520
Writing it down.

179
00:20:30,200 --> 00:20:35,960
Noting frequencies where there are no strong side harmonics.

180
00:20:42,160 --> 00:20:44,080
Moving on.

181
00:20:50,550 --> 00:20:51,930
Another hit.

182
00:20:52,070 --> 00:20:56,370
But here we already see strong side harmonics.

183
00:20:57,510 --> 00:20:58,670
Skipping it.

184
00:21:03,800 --> 00:21:10,540
Side harmonics at 103 kHz too.

185
00:21:21,570 --> 00:21:26,710
Strong side harmonics at 107.7 kHz as well.

186
00:21:27,790 --> 00:21:32,890
And our window of opportunity tops out at 110 kHz.

187
00:21:33,850 --> 00:21:35,190
We've passed it.

188
00:21:35,570 --> 00:21:37,070
Past that, we're not interested.

189
00:21:37,610 --> 00:21:43,550
We can say we have two most likely operating frequencies.

190
00:21:44,950 --> 00:21:52,970
90.8 kHz and 94.5 kHz.

191
00:21:53,790 --> 00:22:01,950
At which the coil gets excited at that strong frequency.

192
00:22:04,970 --> 00:22:13,710
Now let's see which of these falls in our 830–1100 kHz range.

193
00:22:16,330 --> 00:22:20,790
Collapse the spectrogram and see what's happening.

194
00:22:22,970 --> 00:22:27,130
You can see this is the first one we're exciting.

195
00:22:28,390 --> 00:22:33,210
Right now it corresponds to 111 kHz.

196
00:22:33,550 --> 00:22:40,930
Setting our 90.8 kHz.

197
00:22:42,110 --> 00:22:49,970
And we can see the maximum excitation in this high-frequency zone.

198
00:22:49,970 --> 00:22:53,170
And here's one of the peaks.

199
00:22:53,850 --> 00:22:55,770
Now we'll examine it.

200
00:22:58,190 --> 00:23:00,450
Here's our frequency.

201
00:23:00,950 --> 00:23:04,950
First, 90.8 kHz.

202
00:23:05,250 --> 00:23:06,490
And I went to look.

203
00:23:07,710 --> 00:23:11,150
Here's the second peak at 276 kHz.

204
00:23:11,290 --> 00:23:13,310
Looking for high amplitude.

205
00:23:17,570 --> 00:23:31,730
And here we see — one of the peaks from 90.8 kHz hits right at 1 MHz.

206
00:23:33,750 --> 00:23:39,210
And we see it fits beautifully into our window of opportunity.

207
00:23:39,210 --> 00:23:51,090
So by exciting the coil at this frequency, we drive it with both the stable first frequency component and the second one.

208
00:23:51,090 --> 00:23:59,250
And now let's look at 94.5 kHz.

209
00:23:59,450 --> 00:24:00,110
Switching.

210
00:24:01,350 --> 00:24:06,050
94.5.

211
00:24:07,030 --> 00:24:08,570
And looking.

212
00:24:17,910 --> 00:24:27,150
The highest peak hits here too.

213
00:24:28,670 --> 00:24:39,030
But the greatest stability, recall, was near 910 kHz.

214
00:24:40,230 --> 00:24:45,290
And the strongest gain when we put a hand on the coil.

215
00:24:46,150 --> 00:24:51,170
And the strongest amplitude gain during the amplitude measurement.

216
00:24:51,170 --> 00:25:05,200
So we can now conclude that 90.8 kHz is the best choice for push-pull operation, based on the spectrogram.

217
00:25:06,170 --> 00:25:07,430
Marking it.

218
00:25:12,800 --> 00:25:14,840
That's the search method.

219
00:25:15,840 --> 00:25:33,560
To verify, we can switch to our 90.8 kHz, collapse the spectrogram, and check the highest peaks in decibels.

220
00:25:33,560 --> 00:25:39,420
Set it, and yes, it really is 1 MHz on the dot.

221
00:25:40,700 --> 00:25:43,720
And we can switch to another high peak.

222
00:25:47,140 --> 00:25:49,460
Here — the highest one.

223
00:25:51,620 --> 00:25:54,880
That's our 4630.

224
00:26:02,860 --> 00:26:04,400
Here's that peak.

225
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,820
So we've correctly found our frequency.

226
00:26:15,220 --> 00:26:20,700
We can also do one more practical check of the frequencies we've identified.

227
00:26:20,700 --> 00:26:26,200
By matching the beat patterns at different frequencies.

228
00:26:27,080 --> 00:26:32,100
Right now a square wave is being fed at 91 kHz.

229
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:37,220
And we keep watching with the current sensors.

230
00:26:41,670 --> 00:26:44,530
This is the signal we feed in.

231
00:26:45,050 --> 00:26:50,730
It creates oscillations like these in the coil.

232
00:26:50,730 --> 00:26:53,330
We'll watch the beats.

233
00:26:53,430 --> 00:26:57,230
Collapsing the sweep and

234
00:27:12,330 --> 00:27:14,030
we see interesting patterns.

235
00:27:17,950 --> 00:27:27,670
Now let's check whether these patterns — these oscillograms — look the same at the other multiple frequency.

236
00:27:29,630 --> 00:27:37,090
Feed the signal generator 910 kHz.

237
00:27:43,080 --> 00:27:47,740
The oscilloscope now shows the envelope amplitude.

238
00:27:49,220 --> 00:27:55,560
And we see the amplitude grew, but the beats are preserved.

239
00:27:56,520 --> 00:27:58,680
Same shape.

240
00:28:02,480 --> 00:28:03,880
Examined...

241
00:28:04,680 --> 00:28:15,460
Now the sweep is 5 microseconds per division.

242
00:28:18,960 --> 00:28:31,940
And we feed in our main strong frequency — 4630 kHz.

243
00:28:53,940 --> 00:28:55,940
Amplitude off the chart.

244
00:28:57,260 --> 00:29:02,280
Coming back, and we see the familiar fish shape.

245
00:29:02,380 --> 00:29:08,100
That is, we hit the main strong frequency for this coil.

246
00:29:09,760 --> 00:29:18,740
You see this when ramping up with a square signal — you can switch to a sine signal.

247
00:29:21,100 --> 00:29:26,040
Amplitude will drop, but the beats stay.

248
00:29:31,730 --> 00:29:34,210
You can see it at different sweep settings.

249
00:29:36,550 --> 00:29:40,570
The picture holds up to

250
00:29:45,010 --> 00:29:47,970
a sine wave on the main carrier.

251
00:30:07,620 --> 00:30:20,200
And likewise, if the signal is strong enough, the oscilloscope will show the envelope shape — a sine wave on those fish.

252
00:30:20,300 --> 00:30:24,680
We can also measure its frequency.

253
00:30:30,990 --> 00:30:33,710
Switch to cursor measurement mode.

254
00:30:35,810 --> 00:30:37,250
Press pause.

255
00:30:38,250 --> 00:30:40,810
Set the first cursor.

256
00:30:47,910 --> 00:30:48,570
Second.

257
00:30:56,140 --> 00:31:13,250
We can see that the frequency of our beats in this coil is 32.47 Hz.

258
00:31:15,330 --> 00:31:28,270
Which also confirms this isn't a 50 Hz mains pickup, but real processes happening inside this coil.

259
00:31:32,990 --> 00:31:36,050
I verified this result in practice too.

260
00:31:37,470 --> 00:31:41,400
91 kHz was fed in here.

261
00:31:41,400 --> 00:31:51,060
And this coil started warming up very well without any load at this frequency.

262
00:31:51,200 --> 00:31:55,100
Which confirms that the heating is happening in this zone.

263
00:31:56,500 --> 00:32:05,420
By touch — I didn't measure with a thermometer — about 45–50 degrees.

264
00:32:05,560 --> 00:32:09,960
Warming up with around 3 amps of consumption on the push-pull.

265
00:32:11,760 --> 00:32:14,650
The coil is heating up without a load.

266
00:32:15,720 --> 00:32:20,420
Clear current movement along the wire length.

267
00:32:21,940 --> 00:32:24,100
Which is exactly what we want.

268
00:32:26,800 --> 00:32:31,540
You can't do LC resonance directly on push-pull as such.

269
00:32:31,680 --> 00:32:33,340
I'll show this later.

270
00:32:33,760 --> 00:32:39,180
You can't feed 91 kHz directly to the inductor.

271
00:32:39,780 --> 00:32:40,720
What happens?

272
00:32:40,820 --> 00:32:44,100
You can try it of course — everyone has.

273
00:32:44,820 --> 00:32:46,480
And something interesting happens.

274
00:32:46,760 --> 00:32:58,080
If you feed in a frequency equal to the key's operating frequency, here's what we get.

275
00:32:59,300 --> 00:33:00,320
Let me draw it.

276
00:33:01,360 --> 00:33:04,320
Say this is our push-pull frequency.

277
00:33:05,340 --> 00:33:17,660
And we have the signal during the transistor's operation that we're ramping up each half-cycle.

278
00:33:17,660 --> 00:33:40,380
When the Tesla fires at this point — the strike happens practically at maximum, and we'll get what many people have seen from their own experiments — the push-pull power keys blowing.

279
00:33:40,380 --> 00:33:40,980
Blowing.

280
00:33:42,200 --> 00:33:47,580
So to prevent that, the push-pull is driven into a different mode.

281
00:33:47,660 --> 00:34:14,040
As I drew earlier — and a lot of people asked why I drew that picture in another video — where I have the incident wave, as I drew, and the reflected wave.

282
00:34:14,040 --> 00:34:15,260
The reflected one.

283
00:34:15,740 --> 00:34:17,500
And they're in phase.

284
00:34:18,540 --> 00:34:21,440
Lots of questions about why I drew it that way.

285
00:34:21,720 --> 00:34:22,820
Like, that's wrong.

286
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:29,980
We all know from the textbook that a reflected wave comes back 180 degrees out of phase.

287
00:34:30,860 --> 00:34:31,900
All true.

288
00:34:32,220 --> 00:34:34,960
That's the voltage reflection.

289
00:34:35,200 --> 00:34:37,460
For current, we don't think about it that way.

290
00:34:37,680 --> 00:34:55,200
If we have a current-reflected wave in an LC tank with a 180-degree phase shift, that's equivalent to putting two magnets together with like poles facing each other.

291
00:34:55,900 --> 00:35:01,140
You won't see a net boost from a strong magnetic field.

292
00:35:01,820 --> 00:35:09,900
That's why, on push-pull, we get the incident and reflected wave in phase.

293
00:35:10,900 --> 00:35:24,580
You can see this physically by hanging a current sensor on the inductor's tank circuit.

294
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:37,280
And on a single trace you'll see both the wave going out and the one coming back.

295
00:35:37,280 --> 00:35:43,690
It'll copy this wave in phase — you get pretty much this picture.

296
00:35:44,620 --> 00:35:49,710
They go in phase, just at smaller amplitude.

297
00:35:55,600 --> 00:36:13,080
On the push-pull this is achieved by picking the right ratio between the capacitor hung on the inductor's tank and the capacitor hung on the output of our gradient grenade coil.

298
00:36:15,040 --> 00:36:16,540
And what happens?

299
00:36:16,700 --> 00:36:19,840
The push-pull runs at a low frequency.

300
00:36:20,860 --> 00:36:30,920
But when we look on the scope, it'll show us a frequency higher than the main signal frequency.

301
00:36:31,820 --> 00:36:40,680
In my case it turned out my frequency is 91 kHz.

302
00:36:42,420 --> 00:36:52,020
That means the push-pull actually has to run 2 times lower — can drive 3 times lower.

303
00:36:52,460 --> 00:36:53,980
To get this picture.

304
00:36:54,080 --> 00:36:59,160
In practice I even got 3 waves in phase.

305
00:37:00,920 --> 00:37:08,200
That's how it looks on the current sensor — one single phase.

306
00:37:09,820 --> 00:37:15,820
When that happens, we get a strong net magnetic field.

307
00:37:16,300 --> 00:37:28,860
And if we then collapse the sweep, the time per division, you can see some really interesting patterns — the fish.

308
00:37:29,860 --> 00:37:32,320
Why do we need that trick?

309
00:37:33,900 --> 00:37:40,100
We already talked about how, if the Tesla strikes on the fundamental, the transistors blow.

310
00:37:40,380 --> 00:37:54,140
But if we have this picture, then when the Tesla works on free oscillation, we get a sharp current amplitude rise at this point.

311
00:37:54,140 --> 00:38:06,780
When we look at the current transformer we see the picture I showed in the previous video.

312
00:38:07,060 --> 00:38:12,560
The effect of the Tesla transformer on the current in the tank circuit.

313
00:38:13,020 --> 00:38:20,840
The current amplitude jumps up, the sine grows much larger.

314
00:38:20,840 --> 00:38:31,840
And at the same time, the total consumption from the supply feeding the push-pull drops.

315
00:38:33,400 --> 00:38:37,580
Current amplitude grows and consumption drops.

316
00:38:37,580 --> 00:39:03,280
In real numbers — say in normal mode without Tesla operation the push-pull drew 3 amps at 24 volts; with Tesla operation kicking in, in one case it consumes 1 amp at the same 24 volts.

317
00:39:03,280 --> 00:39:06,820
Same 24-volt supply.

318
00:39:09,780 --> 00:39:12,160
Interesting feature.

319
00:39:12,300 --> 00:39:17,140
In the next videos we'll look at how this happens, how it works.

320
00:39:20,600 --> 00:39:22,360
Good luck to everyone with your experiments.
